== 3. Nxe5 ==

'''3. Nxe5''' is the critical move that refutes the Damiano defence. White realised that f6 couldn't defend the e5 pawn because of the weakness of Black's kingside. 

If '''3...fxe5?''' then 4. Qh5+! exploits the open e8-to-h5 diagonal. Then if 4...g6 5. Qxe5+ forks the king and Black's rook on h8. After 5...Qe7 6. Qxh8 (6. Qxe7? and White only has two pawns for the knight) Qxe4+ 7. Kd1, Black has a knight and a pawn for the rook and two pawns they lost.

4...Ke7 does not fare better: 5. Qxe5+ Kf7 6. Bc4+ d5 7. Bxd5+ Kg6 and White has three pawns for their knight, their bishop developed, and Black's king on the run. The [[Chess/Sample_chess_game#3._Nxe5|Chess Wikibook Sample Game]] follows the 3...fxe5 4. Qh5+ Ke7 line.

Therefore, Black can't afford to take the knight. Instead '''3...Qe7''' is their best try. 4. Nf3 Qxe4+ 5. Be2 and Black has at least recovered the pawn, but White has a big development lead. The other goal of 3...Qe7 is to bait 4. Qh5+? from an unsuspecting White player, as here 4. Qh5+ is a mistake because after 4...g6 the queen can't take on e5. 5. Nxg6 Qxe4+ 6. Be2 Qxg6 and Black is up a knight for a pawn.

